description.text:
This is a simple "Air Amplifier" - high pressure air input at the small tube inlet generates an increased volume of air at the output through the use of an annular Venturi arrangement.

This can be printed at this scale with a 0.2mm nozzle and the needed support is already drawn into the file - as it needs to be very specific - once printed, snap out the inner piece from the output side of the Venturi and its ready to go.

If you use a larger nozzle, the inner gap and tube will not form correctly and be supported by the support plug - you would have to scale the whole device so that the lip of the annular opening was one nozzle width or more.

This can even be "powered" by a dust off can -

It was designed to be a layer cooler for my 3D printer using compressed air rather than a fan.

It may come up with three non-manifold edges - which I haven't been able to find yet but my slicer software fixes for me.

description.text:
We were about to make a pork, but had no meat tenderizer (or tenderiser ?). Well, we had an Ikea Fixa hammer, so I made a meat tenderizer head accessory.

it's parametric (customisable / customizable), so you can use Customizer or edit .SCAD file to adjust:

  • Hammer head length & diameter
  • Material thickness
  • Violence level (number & size of spikes)

Included .STL file is for those who have Ikea Fixa hammer (⌀ 26mm, ↨ 15mm) and don't want to mess with customizer.

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

40%

Notes:

Try not to use brim (use either raft or nothing). It's hard to remove the raft+supports and not to break item legs.

Ensure good layer adhesion and sturdy walls/infill so the part won't fracture on your food.

You should assure that the process is safe to your meat:

  1. Use food-safe plastic like PLA. PLA is made of vegetable starch and it's food-safe unless it's dyed with a toxic paint. My PLA vendor assures my filament is biodegradable and food-safe.
  2. Cover meat with a plastic bag while tenderizing (see the last photo)
  3. Ensure good layer adhesion and sturdy structure so the part won't fracture and you have no plastic debris.

The good news are you don't have to worry about cleaning it — the part only weights a gram so it's easier to throw it away and re-print next time it's needed.

title: Silent Mod for EVERY 3d Printer !MUST HAVE! (nema damper)

description.text:
This silent mod is for EVERY 3d printer with Nema17 motors.
The silicone parts reduce the noise in a so drastic matter, the loudes part on the printer is the cooling fan for the hotend now.

It is important that the Nema17 motors and the bolt to hold them have no direct contact to the frame. For this purpose the silicone washers are very important.

The part order is:
bolt - metal washer - silicone washer - frame - silicone plate for Nema17- Nema17 motor

For additoinal vibration reduction i have added a mold for the rubber feet.

If this mod changed you life feel free to donate. :D

Does smell bad curing, and takes more like 24 or 48 hours to cure, but silicone hardens more over time and might need replacing in a year or two.

title: Anet A8  M8 Threaded Rod Filament Spool Holder Mk.I

description.text:
Simple, cheap, easy-to-make sturdy filament spool holder for Anet A8 and other Prusa-style printers.

Why choose this over any of the other holders?

First of all, it's easy to make and doesn't take up much filament. It also gets rid of the large prints you have to sit around and wait for common to frame-mounted filament holders.

Also, it's fairly cheap. Depending on where you live, the necessary materials will cost you at most some 10-20USD/EUR/GBP, most likely a lot, LOT less. Mine ended up costing 2.50EUR for the M8 threaded rod (1 metre, so I was left with extra) and some filament.

It's super simple. Anyone can put this together and even printers with not-so-accurate calibration will manage parts this size with ease. This also saves you filament for printing more cool stuff!

What you'll need for this thing:
-The printed parts, print two (2) of each.
-Some M8 nuts and washers, you can and should reuse the Anet ones.
-Three (3) 20cm/0.65ft/8" long pieces of M8 threaded rod (tip: dollar stores, walmart etc. misc stores most likely sell 1m/9ft rods for very low prices, check those.) You don't need super hard or coated ones, just the basic ones will do.
-A tool for cutting the M8 threaded rod (a hacksaw will do fine). Alternatively you could ask a local auto shop or school/university to cut these if none of your friends, family or relatives have any tools fit for the job.
-Two (2) 608zz or similar bearings with 8mm inner diameter.
-Some thing to tighten and center the spool with, personally I use this one: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2217322

Don't forget to like, comment, collect and post makes! Any feedback or suggestions is gold to me, so don't be shy! Also, if you remix or use parts of this thing in your own things, please give me a shout out and add a link to the original thing!

Printer:

Prusa Clone

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Yes

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

50-100%

Notes:

Material doesn't matter.

For the best results please rotate the models a bit. You might want to use supports (touching buildplate) for the holder ends. The holder mount I found to require no supports.

I strongly suggest 85-100% infill on the holder ends, just to be safe.

Models in the pictures were printed with an Anet A8 using black 1.75mm K-Camel ABS filament, 60mm/s @220°C with a layer height of 0.2mm.

Assembly: Step 1

First, roll some nuts on the M8 threaded rods around where the cuts will be as shown in the picture. This will ensure you get a clean thread after the cut.

Next, cut the M8 threaded rod into three (3) approx. 20cm/0.65ft/8" pieces.

Finally, roll out the nuts through the ends you just cut. This'll clean the thread and force it back into shape.

Assembly: Step 2

Undo the screws holding the Anet A8 display backplate. You don't need to undo them all the way, just until you get the nut out and the end of the screw is level with the acrylic backplate. I suggest doing this one side after another, so you don't have to deal with the backplate dropping.

Next, take the holder mounts and place them against the acrylic bakcplate with the hole facing upwards. Screw in the screws to lock them and the backplate in place. Don't overtighten the screws, you don't need much force! Do this for both sides.

Assembly: Step 3

First, pick two (2) of the rods that are the closest to each other in length.

Next, insert the M8 threaded rods into the holes on the holder ends. It'll go in for approx. 1cm/0.4". Don't force them in any further. If you can't get the rod inserted by hand, use one of the other rod pieces to gently turn the holder end by using the slot on the top.

Finally, roll one m8 nut on both threaded rods. Roll them about halfway up.

Assembly: Step 4

Now, take your threaded rods with the holder ends attached and insert them into the holes on the holder mounts. They should go in for about 3cm/1.2". Again, don't force them further than that.

Once the rods are in place, roll the nuts down and gently tighten them against the holder mounts.

Now you're ready to put the actual spool holder on. Take your printed spool tightener/centerpiece of your choice and put those on the remaining M8 threaded rod along with a nut on each side. Put two (2) nuts and two (2) washers on one end of your threaded rod in the following order: nut-washer-washer-nut. Roll the first nut back until there's enough clearance to place the threaded rod on the slots in the holder ends. Gently tighten the nuts to lock the threaded rod onto the holder end, just like you do with the stock Anet A8 holder.

There you have it! Enjoy your filament holder!

description.text:
Just a simple screw in mount for the I/O POD RTC-EEPROM-TEMP  
RTC - Temperature board.  
Prints just fine without supports..

The Intention was that in every storyline they say "Mech/Titans were build in a fabric".
But i can´t find anything from Warhammer or Online. So i made something. This is an absolute unique idea. Dimension: 25cm x 23cm x 45cm height

Here are the pictures with basic airbrush, 2x blue LED in front, 2x in the back are white. 3x green LED in the top and 1x white for spot light. Now you can print yourself a display unit for your Warhammer stuff. The defense tower is 360° rotable and the LED powerline goes through the middle pin. All planed in.

The plate is self created. Used the terminal from here (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2552113) and part of the barrels (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:418975) for decoration.
The stairs are a mix of pw_jameson (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2246090).
The beams are self created.
The LED Spots are a remix of (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1232648) but i included a reflector. Looks better.
The defense tower is an absolute frankenstein idea. Took the cockpit&side parts of (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2538713) made it hollow, cut out 5mm holes for LED/cables, removed the wings and then build the moving arms. Hold together by 20x3 mm screw.

The file "LED Spots" has the spots, cable lines, holder and stuff inside for building the electricity. For Connecting take the Volt Plate and glue 2x 2Pin Wago Connectors on. Take the holders and put the cable in the cable lines and glue the holders in the steel frames as needed.

For the LED Spots i used normal LED (green, blue, red, white, yellow, blink LED,..) and a 470 Ohm Widerstand. Standard 12 Volt Wiring with LED. To get the needed 12 Volt DC take a 3x18650 holder and 3 Akkus. They bring enough power for 20 hours or more.

ATTENTION: The eyes of the skulls are not going complete through. With bright LED you don´t need, but with coloured standard LED and a black basic coat you need to drill the holes out. I drilled from the back and made a round hole, then push through the eye.
AND DON´T NAIL IN YOUR FINGER. Grr

When you put a 100 Ohm or more Potentiometer (2-3 Euro) between the + cable and the 12 Volt DC Source you can dimm the LED down to zero if it´s too bright. Please check the mcd of your LED you use. You don´t need extra bright LED´s cause your are getting blind when you see it the hole time. Less is sometimes more. Maybe someone can make something for a standard 3x18650 12 Volt DC holder and potentiometer build in? Please.

If you want other weapons for the defense tower contact me with thingi source, then i remix and upload the desired weapon for printing. Blaster, Plasmaguns,...

NEW: The crane is also online. Need some time for printing all and the LED stuff then come the real pictures. Total height with crane: mighty 67 cm
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2657301

The name Warhammer ©, ... are licensed names under Games Workshop ©. I didn´t scanned any stuff, used only Things from Thingiverse. This is an unofficial project not under offizial lizenz of Games Workshop. The rest is completely unique designed to fit with original Space Marines ©, ... from Games Workshop ©. It should also fit on the standard 48x72 playground. If Games Workshop © disagree, please contact me.

Die Idee war, weil immer in den Geschichten steht "Mech/Titans werden in Fabriken gebaut". Leider kann ich nichts dazu bei Warhammer oder sonst Online finden. Daher einfach selbst was gebaut. Maße: 25cm x 23cm x 45cm Höhe.

Türen hab ich zwar auch, doch die sind windschief. Könnt euch ja auch selbst noch welche designen, oder einen Seitenkran? Mal sehn. Sieht ohne aber auch genial aus und Ihr habt eine Displayeinheit bzw. könnt es im Spiel als Werkstatt oder so verwenden.

Hier die Bilder mit Basis Airbrush, 2x blaue LED vorne, 2x weiß hinten. 3x grün für die Schädel und Weiß für den Scheinwerfer. Der Verteidigungstower läßt sich um 360° drehen und das Stromkabel geht in der Mitte durch den Pin. Alles eingeplant.

Die Platte ist selbst gestaltet. Habe das Terminal hier eingebaut (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2552113) und ein paar Fässer aus (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:418975) für Dekoration.
Das Geländer hinten sind Teile von pw_jameson (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2246090).
Die Stahlträger sind selbst gestaltet wie auch das Dach.
Den doppelkopf Adler habe ich nicht eingescannt, sondern eine fertige Vorlage verwendet. Ich habe nichts eingescannt sondern nur eine Kopie des Adlers aus Thingiverse verwendet.
P.S.: Der Adler ist ein Markenzeichen von Games Workshop und egal wer sich hier aufführt sollte sich erst mal den Paragraph über geistiges Eigentum auf der Games Workshop Seite ansehen.

Die LED Spots sind ein Remix von (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1232648) aber ich habe noch Reflektoren ergänzt. Sieht besser aus und Licht streut nicht so arg.

Der Verteidungstower ist ein Frankenstein Projekt gewesen aus (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2538713) ausgehöhlt, Flügel ab, Löcher für LED´s und Kabel, dann die beweglichen Arme dazu. Zusammen gehalten von 2x 20x3 mm Schraube.

Achtung: Die Augen der Totenköpfe gehen nicht komplett durch. Mit weißen oder sehr hellen LED´s braucht Ihr nicht zu bohren. Allerdings mit bunten standart LED´s und schwarzem Basislack habe ich von hinten ein rundes Loch in die Rückseite gemacht. Danach mit etwas spitzem durch die Augen stechen. UND NICHT IN DIE FINGER STECHEN. Grrr

In der Datei LED Spots sind die Spots, Kabelführungen/Verblendungen, Halter, Verteilerplatte um die Elektrik zu verlegen. Auf die Verteilerplatte einfach 2 Wago Klemmen (2pol) aufkleben. Für die LED Spots habe ich einfache standart LED (weiß, gelb, grün, blau, rot) mit 470 Ohm Widerstand für 12 Volt DC verwendet. Um die benötigten 12 Volt zusammen zu bekommen, einfach einen 3fach 18650 Halter kaufen und ein paar Akkus dazu.

Falls Ihr für den Verteidungunsturm andere Waffen möchtet, einfach mit der Thingi Quelle anschreiben, dann kann ich nach dem slicen das gewünschte Modell hoch laden. Plasmakanonen, 1-3 läufige Waffen, gibt vieles für die Mechs/Titans/Knights. Muss aber auch Druckbar sein.

Wenn Ihr zwischen der + Leitung und der 12 Volt DV Quelle einen 100 Ohm oder größer Potentiometer dazwischen macht, könnt Ihr die LED´´s auch noch dimmen. Funktioniert so schon einwandfrei. Könnte vielleicht jemand ein Gehäuse für einen Standard 3x18650 12 DC Halter samt Potentiometer machen? Bitte, hab dafür gerade keinen Nerv. Bzw. welche Connector nimmt man denn da?

NEU: Der Kran ist auch fertig, brauch aber noch zum drucken, LED und Airbrush. Dann kommen noch die echten Bilder. Gesamthöhe mit Kran mächtige 67 cm.

Die Projekt ist aus vielen Vorlagen anderer User zusammen gestellt worden. Ich habe keine Gegenstände von Games Workshop eingescannt. Sollte Games Workshop hier nicht über einstimmen, bitte Kontakt aufnehmen. Leider kann ich nicht den Detailgrad eines Original Teils auf einen 3D Drucker erreichen. I have wooden valences over the plantation shutters in my kitchen. They're held on by these cheap plastic clips that break off.  In fact, all of my valences had been stacked up for 3 years in a corner of my dining room.  Hours of searching local hardware stores and the Internet didn't yield any replacements.  Luckily, I built a Reprap this summer.  I don't even remember the laborious procedure I went through to get an STL, but basically, I started with a photo of the clip, used Photoshop to turn it into a high contrast image, then Inkscape to convert to DXF, and finally, OpenSCAD to extrude it.
Needless to say, this part made my wife extremely happy!
valenceclip4.stl is more like the original, but for extra strength, I used mostly valenceclip4-8mm.stl, which is a bit wider.  You can also change the width with the OpenSCAD script.

comments.text: Finally, these things break all the time and it was on my to-do list bit never got around to modeling them, thanks! Unfortunately, I've moved from that house that had all the valences, but now I know can print them if I ever need them in the future.

description.text:
We recently got a desiccant dehumidifier and although working awesomely pumping out buckets of water - we had no idea how effective it was and what the relative humidity was in our house.
The other half went on Amazon, did a search for Hygrometer and bought the little unit in the photo for a buck or two.
It doesn't stand up easily on it's own and the vents to sample the air are in the back of the unit (not useful if it falls over).
So I put my thinking cap on and fought with OnShape for a few hours to come up with this little design for a self-standing mount.

title: Extruder Tube Cooler for K8200 printer

description.text:
This thing is a nozzle for a small radial blower.  
Attach to your K8200 in order to keep the extruder tube cool during long prints.  
An axial fan could also work here but a 40mm fan is too large and smaller ones are difficult to get. In my opinion the radial fan also fits better behind the extruder and is easy to mount with a few cable ties.

Adjust dimensions in OpenSCAD or Customizer then print with perimeters only ( zero infill and no top/bottom layers ).   
Use glue to attach the nozzle to the blower and cable strips to hold the blower in place.  
I also recommend getting a fan regulator ( FAN MATE 2 or similiar ) because operating the blower at about 7 Volts seems to be optimal.

title: Mavic Pro Controller Bike Handlebar Mount

description.text:
I made a handlebar-mounted holder for my Mavic Pro remote control for a bike ride around Taiwan I did earlier this year.

The controller sits a little loose in the holder but a bit of foam on the inside bottom will make the controller fit snugly and will prevent any rattling noise. Really big bumps or potholes could jar the controller loose, so use at your own risk! For slow smooth rides, though, the holder worked like a charm.

The holder connects to the handlebar via a BioLogic AnchorStrap using an AnchorPoint mount. You can get them here:
https://buy.ternbicycles.com/products/biologic-anchorpoint-bar-mount
https://buy.ternbicycles.com/collections/cases-mounts/products/biologic-anchorstrap

Piloting a drone while riding a bike is never recommended. I merely used this to hold the controller while the drone automatically followed along in Follow Me mode.

description.text:
Are you tired of the AC vent blasting onto your arm? This is a simple air flow redirection towards the ceiling of the cab. This will not only cool the car evenly but also redirect the flow to the top of the car where majority of the heat resides.

*use design at your own risk, design may vary from model to model.

EDIT: New version uploaded extending the vent by 3mm gives a cleaner fit. Use DefenderAirVent_02.stl

Printer Brand:

Prusa

Printer:

Prusa Mk2

Resolution:

0.3

Infill:

35

Mounting Options

To mount this to your land rover defender there are various options.

1.) Use duck-tape/Gaffer-tape to secure it, allows you flip it up for more direct air flow.

2.) 3M double-sided Adhesive tape; Add a strip to the underside of the top "lip" and press firmly down for 10-15 seconds.

*Note these are non-destructive ways to mount it, you may also use your combination of glues that works for you.

Designing the Air Vent

This was designed on a 2016 Land Rover Defender and (should) fit all Land Rover Defender from 2006 onwards. In order to get the curves correctly various tracing, sketching and computer-tracing was required, earlier models may have variations in their design that may make this design not fit properly, if so please comment below and I will try my best to adjust the design.

description.text:
Description

A frame support I designed for my Tarantula around the 6mm threaded rods I already had.

Printed parts list

1 x Upper support
2 x Upper rod end
2 x Rod end
2 x Lower support

Non printed parts list

Threaded rods: 2 x M6x430mm. Can be longer but shorter will make the angles smaller and support not so rigid.
Washers: 6 x Ø6; 8 x Ø5
Nuts: 8 x M6; 4 X M5
Bolts: 4 x M5x25mm

Functional description

I wanted to make my printer frame more rigid. So I mounted it to am MDF plate that I had and printed a bracket. But it looked wery weak after printing and I decided to make something stable. Found those threaded rods I had from before and desighed this using them as main piece for adjustment and stability.

Printing tips

Since those are structural parts print slower for beter filament adhesion. Should be printed in the orientations showed in the screenshot so the forces will be along the strands. Supports are needed only on those parts shown on the screenshot.

Installation and adjustment

1) Install everything as shown in the photo. Dont tighten the nuts.
2) Tighten the upper nuts at lower rod ends to fix the screws\
3) Adjust the frame to be perpendicular to the mount plate by tightening/loosening the top nuts at Upper rod ends.
4) Tighten counter nuts and transverse M5 bolts/nuts to fix everything.

Others

Designed in: eMachineShop
Attached files: STL and EMS
Material: used PLA(blue) but after some time Upper rod end delaminated so I redesigned it and reprinted in PETG(black).

title: Warhammer Quest (1995) Taurian Proxies
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I'm working on a complete set of printed proxies to cover the entire range of possible rolls on all 10 levels of the monster tables from the WHQ Roleplay Book.

I only ever owned the base set, and I always wanted to collect them all but could never afford it when they were still on the market.

I've leaned heavily on dutchmogul's amazing collection of gaming miniatures. Some of these figures are only resized versions of his, some are modded versions of his, and a rare few are scratch modeled by me.

I've gone through the list and pared it down as much as possible. My goal is to handle any given roll, but not worry about trying to cover any two rolls... I chose not to distinguish between a Savage Ork and a Black Ork, for example, and I only considered An Ork to differ from and Ork champion if they could both appear on the same roll. I wasn't too uptight about hand weapons... Swords, Spears, Axes... whatever. So you basically end up with Orks, a Big Ork, and a Bigger Ork. Finally, if you have 2D6 goblins that you roll for bows or spears, I choose to take that as 1D6 w/bow and 1D6 with spears to keep the numbers down, but print as many as you want!

This is the Centaurs & Minotaurs, up to battle level 10. The centaurs aren't Centaurs, but their are excellent and fitting models until I (or someone) models true Centaurs. They'll do for Bull Centaurs too, but the idea of Chaos Dwarf torsos on centaurs is a fun one... More races to follow.

3 Centaurs
3 Centaur Champions
1 Centaur Hero(or Lord)
1 Minotaur
3 Minotaur Champions

I deeply appreciate tips if you like my work, but in this case please consider sending some love dutchmogul's way, as his amazing work made this possible!
